'''[[Capital punishment]] in [[Nauru]]''' was used prior to its independence in 1968. Prior to the abolition of capital punishment on 12 May 2016, with the passage of the ''Crimes Act 2016'', [[Amnesty International]] categorised Nauru as abolitionist in practice.<ref>[http://www.amnestyusa.org/pdfs/DeathSentencesAndExecutions2014_EN.pdf Death Sentences and Executions (Amnesty International), 2014).]</ref>

==International agreements==
Nauru is not yet party to the [[Second Optional Protocol to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights|Second Optional Protocol]] to the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]]. In December 2012, Nauru voted in favour of the Resolution on a Moratorium on the Use of the Death Penalty at the [[United Nations General Assembly]].<ref>[https://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/67/176 GA Resolution 2012.]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911215057/http://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A%2FRES%2F67%2F176 |date=September 11, 2016 }}</ref> Nauru was not present for the most recent vote in the UN General Assembly on a moratorium on the death penalty in December 2014.<ref>[https://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A/RES/69/186 GA Resolution 2014.]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413152628/http://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=A%2FRES%2F69%2F186 |date=April 13, 2016 }}</ref>

